<DOC><DOCNO> AP880412-0003 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0001EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-LongHijackings     04-12 0184</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Long Hijackings,0188</SECOND><HEAD>Longest Ordeals of Captives of Hijacked Planes</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Hijack Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The hijacking drama of a Kuwaiti airliner seized April 5 enteredits second week today. Here is a list of prolonged hijack incidents:      JULY 23-SEPT. 1, 1968 _ El Al flight from Rome to Tel Aviv,Israel, is diverted to Algeria by Arab nationalists. Forty dayslater, Algeria releases the last 12 passengers held hostage.   SEPT. 6-30, 1970 _ Palestinian commandos hijack three airlinersto a desert airstrip outside Amman, Jordan. Most passengers arereleased by Sept. 12, when the Palestinians blow up the threeplanes, but 54 people are held hostage for 24 days.   JUNE 15-JULY 1, 1985 _ Shiite Moslem gunmen hijack TWAAthens-to-Rome flight to Beirut. Some passengers are released but40 men are held hostage. One hostage, U.S. Navy diver RobertStetham, is shot dead; 17 days later the remaining 39 are released.   MARCH 2-15, 1981 _ Pakistani hijackers commandeer Pakistani jet,diverting it to Afghanistan and on to Syria. All 148 hostages arereleased after 13 days aboard the plane.</TEXT></DOC>